# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1997-welsh-devolution-referendum
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1832-united-kingdom-general-election-in-wales] The **1832 United Kingdom general election in Wales** was the first election held under the Reform Act 1832 and the Parliamentary Boundaries Act 1832.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1832-united-kingdom-general-election-in-wales] Wales saw its numbers of Members increased from 27 to 32, which includes Monmouthshire, which at the time was sometimes considered part of England.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1832-united-kingdom-general-election-in-wales] The Whigs, under the leadership of the Earl Grey won 18 seats (12 uncontested), against 14 (11 uncontested) for the Duke of Wellington's Tories.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1835-united-kingdom-general-election-in-wales] The **1835 United Kingdom general election in Wales** was held in early 1835, as the Sir Robert Peel's newly formed Conservative Party sought to strengthen its position in Parliament.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1835-united-kingdom-general-election-in-wales] The Whigs, under the leadership of the Viscount Melbourne, despite losing 98 seats, survived in the majority through an alliance with the Irish Radicals.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1835-united-kingdom-general-election-in-wales] In Wales specifically, The Whigs won 15 seats (11 uncontested), against 17 (11 uncontested) for the Conservatives, a shift of 3 seats from Whigs to Conservatives.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1837-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1837 United Kingdom general election** was held from 24 July to 18 August 1837, following the death of King William IV and the accession of Queen Victoria.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1837-united-kingdom-general-election] The election saw the Whigs secure their fourth consecutive victory, though the Conservatives, led by Robert Peel, continued to gain ground.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1837-united-kingdom-general-election] The election marked the last time that a Parliament was dissolved as a result of the demise of the Crown.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1837-united-kingdom-general-election] The dissolution of Parliament six months after a demise of the Crown, as provided for by the Succession to the Crown Act 1707, was abolished by the Reform Act 1867.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1841-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1841 United Kingdom general election** was held between 29 June and 22 July 1841.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1841-united-kingdom-general-election] Following increasing government defeats, the Conservatives under Sir Robert Peel won a decisive victory against the governing Whigs.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1841-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservatives campaigned mainly on an 11-point programme modified from their previous electoral effort and designed by Peel, whilst the Whigs emphasised reforming the import duties on corn, replacing the existing sliding scale with a uniform rate.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1841-united-kingdom-general-election] The Whig position lost them support amongst protectionists, and the Whigs saw heavy losses in constituencies like the West Riding, where aristocratic Whig families who held a strong tradition of unbroken representation in Parliament were rejected by the electorate.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1841-united-kingdom-general-election] O'Connell, who had been governing with the Whigs through a compact, felt the government's unpopularity rub off on him.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1841-united-kingdom-general-election] His own party was shattered in the election.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1841-united-kingdom-general-election] Barely a dozen Repealers retained their seats, and O'Connell himself lost in Dublin while his son was defeated in Carlow.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1841-united-kingdom-general-election] The Chartists picked up only a few votes.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1847-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1847 United Kingdom general election** was held from 29 July to 26 August 1847.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1847-united-kingdom-general-election] It saw the Conservatives win the most seats but remain divided between Protectionists and Peelites.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1847-united-kingdom-general-election] This allowed the Whigs, led by Prime Minister Lord John Russell, to retain power.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1847-united-kingdom-general-election] The general election was held amid the Great Irish famine.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1847-united-kingdom-general-election] The Irish Repeal group won more seats than in the previous general election, while the Chartists gained the only seat they were ever to hold, Nottingham's second seat, held by Chartist leader Feargus O'Connor.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1847-united-kingdom-general-election] The election also witnessed the election of Britain's first Jewish MP, the Liberal Lionel de Rothschild in the City of London.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1847-united-kingdom-general-election] Members being sworn in were however required to swear the Christian Oath of Allegiance, meaning Rothschild was unable actually to take his seat until the passage of the Jews Relief Act in 1858.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1847-united-kingdom-general-election] The constituency of Sudbury, which elected two members, was disfranchised for this election.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1847-united-kingdom-general-election] This accounts there being two fewer seats in the House of Commons as compared to the previous election, though no redistribution took place.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1852 United Kingdom general election** was held from 7 to 31 July 1852.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] It produced a closely contested result between the Conservatives and Whigs, marking a significant shift in British politics, with the Conservatives increasingly representing the rural aristocracy and the Whigs the urban bourgeoisie.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] As in the previous election of 1847, Lord John Russell's Whigs won the popular vote, but the Conservative Party won a very slight majority of the seats.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] However, a split between Protectionist Tories, led by the Earl of Derby, and the Peelites who supported Lord Aberdeen made the formation of a majority government very difficult.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] Lord Derby's minority, protectionist government ruled from 23 February until 17 December 1852.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] Derby appointed Benjamin Disraeli as Chancellor of the Exchequer in this minority government.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] However, in December 1852, Derby's government collapsed because of issues arising out of the budget introduced by Disraeli.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] A Peelite–Whig-Radical coalition government was then formed under Lord Aberdeen.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] Although the immediate issue involved in this vote of "no confidence" which caused the downfall of the Derby minority government was the budget, the real underlying issue was the repeal of the Corn Laws which Parliament had passed in June 1846 and had split the Conservative Party.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] In this election, there were 18 Peelites elected in England and Wales.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The constituency of St Albans, with its two members, was disfranchised due to corruption.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] This accounts for the fact that there were two fewer seats in the House of Commons as compared to the previous election, though no redistribution took place.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] A group within the Tory/Conservative Party called the "Peelites" voted with the Whigs to achieve the repeal of the Corn Laws.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The Peelites were so named because they were followers of Prime Minister Robert Peel.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] In June 1846, when Peel was the Prime Minister of a Tory government, he led a group of Tory/Conservatives to vote with the minority Whigs against a majority of his own party.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] "Corn" was important to the cost of living of the average person in Britain during the early 19th century.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The term "corn" did not refer to maize, as it did in the United States.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] In Britain, "corn" refers to wheat, rye and/or other grains.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] Wheat, or corn, was used in the baking of bread and was the "staff of life".
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] Thus the price of wheat was a very substantial part of the cost of living.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The Corn Laws enforced a very high "protective" tariff against the importation of wheat into England.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] These high tariffs raised the cost of living and increased the suffering of poor people in England.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] Agitation for the repeal of the Corn Laws had begun in England as early as 1837, and bills for their repeal had been introduced in Parliament each year from 1837 until their actual repeal in 1847.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] For some parliamentary leaders, like John Bright, Richard Cobden and Charles Pelham Villiers, the repeal of tariffs on imported corn was not enough.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] They wished to reduce the tariffs on all imported consumer products.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] These parliamentary leaders became known as "free traders".
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The repeal of the Corn Laws irrevocably split the Tory/Conservative party.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The Peelites were not free traders, but both the Peelites and the free traders were originally Tories.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] Thus both the free traders and the Peelites tended to side with the Whigs against the Tories on international trade issues.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] This presented a real threat to any government the Tories attempted to form.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The effect of this split was felt in the election of July–August 1847, when the Whig party won a 53.8% majority of seats in Parliament.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The Whigs knew that they could count on the Peelite Conservatives when an international trade issue came before Parliament.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] In June 1852, the effects of the split in the Tory/Conservative party was having even more effect.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The period after about 1847 was one of economic stagnation in Britain.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The split in the Tory party was a significant cause of the reformation of the political parties in Britain in the February 1852 election.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] As noted above, in the election of 1852 the protectionist rump of the Conservatives became the party of the rural landholders, while the Liberals and Peelites became the party of the towns, boroughs and growing urban industrial areas of Britain.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] In 1852, England elected 244 Conservatives and 216 non-Conservatives; Wales elected 20 Conservatives and 12 non-Conservatives, Scotland elected 20 Conservatives and 33 non-Conservatives, Ireland elected 40 Conservatives and 63 non-Conservatives whereas the Universities elected 6 Conservatives.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The election of 1852 returned a majority in support of free-trade, but the minority Conservative government continued in office.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] An opportunity for the opposition arose in December 1852, when the Chancellor of the Exchequer, Benjamin Disraeli, introduced the budget of the Derby minority government.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] Due to the worsening economic situation, the budget imposed a number of tax increases on the profits of the middle class and granted some tax cuts for the rural landed aristocracy.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The budget also extended the income tax to the Irish middle class, angering some of the members from Ireland who had supported the minority government on the Irish Church issue and were opposed to the previous Prime Minister, the Liberal leader Lord John Russell.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] Consequently, a number of Irish Conservatives voted against the minority government on the Disraeli budget on 17 December 1852.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] This vote of "no confidence" caused the government to fall.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] Following the fall of the minority government, Lord Aberdeen was called on to form a government, since the Irish Conservatives who opposed Disraeli's budget were opposed to Lord John Russell on religious issues and he formed a Peelite/Whig coalition government on 19 December 1852.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] This government served until 30 January 1855, when it too collapsed due to issues surrounding British involvement in the Crimean War.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] While the Conservatives had, in theory, a slim majority over the Whigs, the party was divided between Protectionist and Peelite wings: the former numbered about 290 and the latter 35–40.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The Whigs themselves represented a coalition of old Whigs (conservative Protestant/dissenter aristocrats), Liberals, Radicals, and Irish nationalists.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The above numbers therefore do not represent the true balance of support in Parliament.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1859 United Kingdom general election** was held from 28 April to 18 May 1859 following the defeat of Prime Minister the Earl of Derby's Conservative government in a vote of confidence.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] The newly formed Liberal Party, led by Viscount Palmerston, secured victory despite winning fewer seats than in the previous election.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] There is no separate tally of votes or seats for the Peelites.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] They did not contest elections as an organised party but more as independent Free trade Conservatives with varying degrees of distance from the two main parties.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] It was also the last general election entered by the Chartists, before their organisation was dissolved.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] As of 2024, this is the last election in which the Conservatives won the most seats in Wales.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] The election was the quietest and least competitive between 1832 and 1885, with most county elections being uncontested.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] The election also saw the lowest number of candidates between 1832 and 1885, with Tory gains potentially being the result of a lack of opposition as much as a change in public opinion.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] the government which Palmerston organized in June 1859 was a coalition of a different kind: not a coalition of groups which looked back to the past, but a coalition which anticipated the future.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] Had it not been for Palmerston himself—too individual, too full of personality to be fitted into a party-pattern—it would have been the first Liberal government in our history.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] Everything that was important in it was Liberal—finance, administrative reform, its very composition: the first government with unmistakable middle-class Free Traders as members.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The **1997 Welsh devolution referendum** was a pre-legislative referendum held in Wales on 18 September 1997 over whether there was support for the creation of a National Assembly for Wales, and therefore a degree of self-government.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The referendum was a Labour manifesto commitment and was held in their first term after the 1997 election under the provisions of the Referendums (Scotland and Wales) Act 1997.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] This was the second referendum held in Wales over the question of devolution: the first referendum was held in 1979 and was defeated by a large majority.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The referendum resulted in a narrow majority in favour, which led to the passing of the Government of Wales Act 1998 and the formation of the National Assembly for Wales in 1999.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] A referendum was held in 1979 (with a parallel referendum in Scotland) proposing the creation of a Welsh Assembly, under James Callaghan's Labour government.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The referendum stipulated that a Welsh Assembly would be created if supported by 50% of votes cast and 40% of the total electorate.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The Scottish referendum achieved the first condition but not the second, while the Welsh referendum was defeated by almost a 4:1 majority.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] Indeed, although the Labour Party had committed itself to devolution in 1974 (following the advice of the Royal Commission on the Constitution) several Welsh Labour MPs (including Neil Kinnock) were very much opposed.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The 1979 referendum had been such a resounding defeat that it killed off any prospects of devolution in Wales for a generation.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The almost wholly anti-devolution, unionist Conservative Party won the 1979 general election (though Welsh Labour remained the largest party in Wales, the Conservatives only won 11 out of 36 seats in Wales) and remained in government until 1997.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] Over this time, the Conservative Party became increasingly unpopular in Wales.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] A commitment to the creation of a Welsh Assembly with executive powers was again put into the Labour Party manifesto for the 1992 general election.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The Labour Party shaped its policy of a Welsh Assembly under the guidance of Shadow Welsh Secretary Ron Davies and Welsh Office spokesmen Win Griffiths and Rhodri Morgan.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] In March 1996, Ron Davies signed an agreement with Alex Carlile, the Leader of the Welsh Liberal Democrats, which committed both parties to support a "Yes" vote in a Welsh devolution referendum in the event of a Labour victory at the 1997 general election.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The agreement was made in the context of a potential Lib-Lab pact should Labour not win an overall majority.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] There was no inter-party Constitutional Convention in Wales to define devolution as there had been in Scotland.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] Labour's initial proposal to elect a Welsh Assembly using the traditional first-past-the-post system was reversed in late-1996 in favour of the Additional-member system.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] This change was vital in order to gain the support of Plaid Cymru and the Welsh Liberal Democrats in the event of a referendum.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] Unusually for a referendum just as in the 1997 Scottish devolution referendum the electorate was asked to vote on two statements rather than a question which corresponded to the following proposal.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The statements were issued both in English and Welsh.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The official Yes campaign, *Yes for Wales*, was supported by Labour, the Liberal Democrats and Plaid Cymru, though they also ran their own individual campaigns.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] Labour anti-devolution MPs (including Llew Smith, among others) were subject to a tight parliamentary whip to ensure that the Labour Party was seen to be publicly behind the campaign.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] *Yes for Wales* placed a large emphasis on grassroots involvement in the campaign, with sectoral groups such as "Pensioners say Yes", and local branches throughout Wales.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The official No campaign, *Just Say NO*, was chaired by Nick Bourne, then-Conservative "Chief Spokesman in Wales".
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The No campaign lacked the structure and finance of the Yes campaign, and suffered from the fact that the Conservatives' landslide defeat at the 1997 general election meant there were no Conservative MPs (and therefore no MPs supporting the No campaign) in Wales.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] Additionally, the No campaign in 1997 did not have the support of local authorities; the fact that the Conservatives had reduced layers of local government from two to one in 1994 meant that this was not an issue as it had been in 1979.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] Note: In Wales under the Welsh Language Act 1993 the Welsh language has equal status with the English language.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The overall result was declared in the Royal Welsh College of Music and Drama in Cardiff.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The proceeding officer was Professor Eric Sunderland.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The results of all 22 local authority areas were announced individually, and the result was close enough that everything in fact hung on the announcement from Carmarthenshire, which carried the Yes vote.
[src:1997-welsh-devolution-referendum/1997-welsh-devolution-referendum] The difference between the 'agree' and 'disagree' vote was 6,721.
